enitor in the advancement of democracy, then we need to consider five areas of change that have been significant across national contexts amid both globalization and neoliberalism: inequality, privatization, the public good, identity, and academic freedom. Taking a comparative approach and drawing on scholarly literature, archival research, and interviews, Higher Education for Democracy aims to understand these changes and their implications and to position higher education in defense of democracy in a globalized economy framed by fascism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil society. 0aDemocracy and education. 0aEducation, HigherxAims and objectives. 0aEducation, HigherxPolitical aspects. 0aEducation, Higher--Aims and objectives. 0aEducation, Higher--Political aspects. 0aUniversities and collegesxPolitical aspects. 0aUniversities and colleges--Political aspects. 4aAmerican Studies : American Culture. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aEducation : Education. 4aPolitics and Law : Democracy. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848451840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438484518423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438484518/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles